{"title":"Learning Actions from Human Demonstration Video for Robotic Manipulation","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"General video-to-command methods for robotic imitation rely on video captioning that emphasizes global scene understanding and is insensitive to the specific manipulated object and its state change, leading to errors in complex pick-and-place tasks.","method":"Introduce a captioning network (CNet) that fuses global frame features with a local Video Difference Map (VDM). The VDM is computed as the difference between color masks of the start and end frames, where the color masks are produced by a trained grasp network (GNet) to suppress illumination/shadow effects. Features from uniformly sampled frames and the VDM are extracted with a pre-trained CNN and fed into an LSTM encoder-decoder, modifying the first LSTM layer to connect F(I) and F(V) to half of the input units to specialize inputs. This fusion yields large gains over V2C on BLEU-4, METEOR, ROUGE-L, and CIDEr (e.g., CIDEr 4.676 vs 1.437 with Inception v3)."},{"problem":"For executing the generated commands, the robot needs reliable grasp poses and object categories from RGBD images, while also supplying localized object features to aid captioning.","method":"Propose GNet, an end-to-end grasp detection network that couples SegNet-based object segmentation with a grasp solution generator and an object classifier. From each object mask, the grasp generator computes the center and orientation by fitting a convex hull and minimum-area rectangle; a color mask of the object region mitigates illumination/shadow and is fed to a CNN classifier to predict a 17-way category label. Segmentation and classification are jointly optimized with a multi-task loss. On a UR5, GNet-RGBD achieves a 93% grasp success rate, outperforming baselines and GNet-RGB, demonstrating the benefit of depth."}]}
